## Use Case

I'm using `bevy_state` `States` and `bevy_enhanced_input` `InputContext` side by side. Each state has a matching context:

```rust
// bevy_state
enum RoadToolState { Idle, Active }
enum RoadToolMode { Creating, Extending, Editing }  // SubState of Active

// bevy_enhanced_input
struct CreatingContext;   // ↔ RoadToolMode::Creating
struct ExtendingContext;  // ↔ RoadToolMode::Extending
struct EditingContext;    // ↔ RoadToolMode::Editing
```

They're both answering "what mode is the user in?" but I have to sync them manually. I keep writing `OnEnter` + `DespawnOnExit` for each pair, and I've already hit bugs where contexts leaked or observers didn't attach. Would be nice to just declare the relationship once.

## Problem

When using `bevy_state` alongside `bevy_enhanced_input`, states and contexts must be manually synchronized:

```rust
// Current: Manual spawn/despawn per state
app.add_systems(OnEnter(GameMode::Playing), spawn_player_context);

fn spawn_player_context(mut commands: Commands) {
    commands
        .spawn((
            PlayerContext,
            DespawnOnExit(GameMode::Playing),  // Easy to forget
            actions!(PlayerContext[...]),
        ))
        .observe(on_move)   // Re-attached every state entry
        .observe(on_jump);
}
```

**Pain points:**

- Forgetting `DespawnOnExit` causes context leaks (wrong inputs fire in wrong state)
- Observers re-attached on every state transition
- Boilerplate for every state-context pair
- Two sources of truth that can desync

## Proposed Solution

Declare state-context binding once using `ContextActivity<C>` under the hood:

```rust
// Proposed: Declarative binding, spawn once
fn setup_contexts(mut commands: Commands) {
    commands
        .spawn((
            PlayerContext,
            ActiveInState::<GameMode, PlayerContext>::new(GameMode::Playing),
            actions!(PlayerContext[...]),
        ))
        .observe(on_move)   // Attached once
        .observe(on_jump);
}
```

A sync system toggles `ContextActivity::<C>::ACTIVE/INACTIVE` on state transitions.

## API Sketch

```rust
/// Activates context C when state S matches the specified value.
#[derive(Component)]
pub struct ActiveInState<S: States, C: InputContext> {
    pub state: S,
    _marker: PhantomData<C>,
}

/// Activates context C when state S matches ANY of the specified values.
#[derive(Component)]
pub struct ActiveInStates<S: States, C: InputContext> {
    pub states: Vec<S>,
    _marker: PhantomData<C>,
}
```

